THE RISK:
{
 "id": "serviceable-factor-conflation",
 "title": "The 0.55 serviceable factor conflates 'segments we'd like' with 'compliance-cleared demand' — the corpus puts the reachable slice below the band's floor",
 "narrative": "serviceableFactor 0.55 is the model's only pure assumption leaf on the SAM path, justified by three EU cert regimes cited qualitatively. The corpus disagrees in two directions at once: every quantified B2B analogue found puts SAM far below 45–65% of TAM (worked examples near 12%), and the search surfaced a materially larger regulatory stack than the node cites — WEEE, RoHS, EORI customs registration, the 2024/1364 DC rating scheme, and EED 2024/1791 KPI/waste-heat disclosure. Each omitted instrument is a compliance artifact with lead time that gates tender prequalification. For a pre-launch entrant in its first 12 months, the demand that is actually open to bid is not 55% of TAM; it is the fraction whose tenders it can prequalify for before certifications complete — plausibly below 0.40, under the band's floor for a reason the band never encoded.",
 "category": "model-structure",
 "targetNodes": [
  "serviceableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The 0.55 is unanchored: the only quantified analogues in the corpus are SAM examples near 12% of TAM and SOM benchmarks of 1–10%, all far below the 0.45–0.65 band; simultaneously the cited cert basis (EN 50600, 2019/424, CE/TÜV) omits WEEE, RoHS, EORI, 2024/1364, and EED 2024/1791",
   "refs": [
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c11",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c8",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c9",
    "ledger:serviceableFactor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Each omitted instrument lands as a procurement gate: EED KPI and waste-heat disclosure obligations and the 2024/1364 rating scheme flow into operator tender prequalification, so demand from compliance-sensitive large operators (the venture's declared first channel) is closed to an entrant mid-certification during exactly its first 12 months",
   "refs": [
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c9",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c10",
    "profile:Stage",
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The serviceable share of TAM for the Year-1 window sits below the 0.45 floor; SAM contracts beyond anything the tornado shows, and YAM contracts with it even at the curated 3% obtainable rate",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:serviceableFactor",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The node already carries a wide band (0.45–0.65) and cites real EU regulations, so it reads as a conservatively handled assumption. The hidden failure is definitional: 0.55 was set as 'share of segments we intend to serve', while the funnel needs 'share of demand whose tenders we can prequalify for in the first 12 months' — two different quantities that happen to share a slider.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "A bottom-up channel-coverage model (named CE accounts × compliance-cleared demand, the node's own promotion path) yielding a serviceable share ≥0.50 for the Year-1 window.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.45,
  "rationale": "The corpus documents both the missing regulatory instruments and the absence of any benchmark supporting 0.45–0.65; but part of the gap may be definitional slack rather than a true foreclosure, and mid-market buyers are less prequalification-heavy [evidence revision: Evidence confirms both premises of the trigger: the omitted regulatory stack is real and mandatory, and B2B SAM norms treat serviceable share as reachability-constrained (12% example). This modestly strengthens the hypothesis. But the corpus does not quantify the venture-specific serviceable share below 0.45, and the definitional-slack / less-prequalification-heavy mid-market caveats remain unresolved, so the increase is bounded.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "serviceableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.38,
   "note": "Year-1 compliance-cleared, channel-reachable share; below the band floor per corpus benchmarks and the expanded cert stack"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Certification and disclosure requirements appearing in CE operator PDU/rack-power tender prequalification lists",
   "where": "Frankfurt/Amsterdam/Warsaw colocation procurement packages; hyperscaler supplier-onboarding portals",
   "threshold": "EED 2024/1791 KPI or 2024/1364 rating-scheme references in ≥2 of first 5 target-account tenders",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Implementation timeline and scope of the EU DC rating scheme and EED delegated acts",
   "where": "EUR-Lex / European Commission energy-efficiency dockets for Directive 2024/1791 and Delegated Regulation 2024/1364",
   "threshold": "Supplier-facing obligations confirmed to apply at equipment-procurement level within 12 months",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Own certification program milestones vs plan (CE, TÜV, RoHS/WEEE registration, EORI)",
   "where": "Internal cert tracker vs notified-body lead-time quotes",
   "threshold": "Any critical cert slipping past month 6 of the launch window",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Build the bottom-up channel-coverage model named in the node's promotion path: list the top 50 CE accounts, map each one's prequalification requirements, and compute the compliance-cleared share directly",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "serviceableFactor",
   "note": "Replaces the conflated slider with two separate, measurable quantities"
  },
  {
   "action": "Front-load the full certification stack (including WEEE/RoHS/EORI, not just CE/TÜV) before launch rather than sequencing it with revenue",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Converts the Year-1 foreclosure into a cost line"
  },
  {
   "action": "Route early sales through a distributor/integrator that already holds operator framework qualifications, inheriting their compliance clearance",
   "type": "contractual",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Buys reach into prequalification-gated demand during the certification gap"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "EED Compliance in Data Centres: Why Retrofitting Your PDUs May Be the Smartest Move!",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Schleifenbauer",
   "date": "2025-10-23",
   "excerpt": "The EU Energy Efficiency Directive (EED) has made energy measurement and reporting mandatory for organisations across Europe... What used to be encouraged has now become obligatory.",
   "url": "https://www.schleifenbauer.eu/en/eed-compliance/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "TAM vs SAM vs SOM: How to Calculate Each for B2B (With Real Examples)",
   "sourceType": "analyst-estimate",
   "publisher": "Landbase",
   "date": "2024-05-01",
   "excerpt": "SAM is the portion you can realistically reach with your current product and go-to-market... They use top-down analyst reports that overcount... and never validate their TAM against real company data.",
   "url": "https://www.landbase.com/blog/tam-vs-sam-vs-som-calculate-b2b-2026",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "EU WEEE_RoHS",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "U.S. Department of Commerce (trade.gov)",
   "date": null,
   "excerpt": "Companies selling electrical and electronic goods in the European Union must conform to the EU legislation for electrical and electronic equipment (EEE)... national rules for implementing each directive will differ from country to country.",
   "url": "https://www.trade.gov/eu-weeerohs",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.schleifenbauer.eu/en/eed-compliance/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "The EU Energy Efficiency Directive (EED) has made energy measurement and reporting mandatory for organisations across Europe."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.trade.gov/eu-weeerohs",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Companies selling electrical and electronic goods in the European Union must conform to the EU legislation for electrical and electronic equipment (EEE)."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.idcpdu.com/news/industry-news/pdu-rohs-and-ce-certifications-buyer-guide.html",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "RoHS and CE are not box-ticking labels—they directly affect market access, shipment timing, product safety, and legal exposure."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.landbase.com/blog/tam-vs-sam-vs-som-calculate-b2b-2026",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "SAM is the portion you can realistically reach with your current product and go-to-market. SOM is the portion you can actually capture in the near term given your resources, competition, and execution capacity."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://scalarly.com/blog/tam-sam-som-market-sizing-framework/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "you might estimate the European mid-market segment at 12% of the total"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://umbrex.com/resources/market-sizing-playbook/bottom-up-market-sizing-methodology/",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "It begins with the atomic units of demand—individual customers, devices, transactions, square feet—and scales upward through explicit assumptions on penetration, pricing, and usage."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://intelligence.uptimeinstitute.com/resource/2024-spending-and-supply-chain-survey-results-and-crosstab-files",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "focuses on data center spending and budgets, as well as plans going forward and data center supply chains"
  }
 ]
}

